Bhikkhu Kaṭukurunde Ñāṇananda — Nibbāna: The Mind Stilled

Access status: official free-distribution PDF/HTML/audio. Seeing Through the Net hosts the 33-sermon set, HTML edition, complete download, and audio files. The 2019 library PDF states “Published strictly for free distribution” and “All Rights Reserved,” so use summary-heavy treatment and only short quotes.

1. Source Identity

Source: Nibbāna: The Mind Stilled
Author: Bhikkhu Kaṭukurunde Ñāṇananda
Form: 33 sermons on Nibbāna, originally delivered at Nissarana Vanaya between 1988 and 1991.


Lineage: Sri Lankan forest Theravāda, early Buddhist sutta hermeneutics, phenomenological Dhamma analysis.
Imaginarium use: primary source for “de-rendering” the self-world: how signs, name-and-form, consciousness, perception, contact, craving, and conceptual proliferation fabricate the lived world.

2. Buddhist Lineage Placement

Ñāṇananda’s Nibbāna: The Mind Stilled is the central phenomenological and dependent-arising reading of Nibbāna. It treats Nibbāna not as a metaphysical object, heaven, blank annihilation, or mystical substance, but as the stilling of the machinery that renders saṃsāric experience.

Compared with the other core sources:

Ñāṇavīra gives the existential skeleton: self-view, structure, reflexivity, contradiction.
Ṭhānissaro gives the practical breath-fabrication training.
Concept and Reality gives the theory of papañca.
The Magic of the Mind gives the illusion/magic-show model.
The Law of Dependent Arising gives the systematic causal engine.
Nāgārjuna radicalizes emptiness and dependent designation.
Visuddhimagga systematizes the path architecture.
Buddhadāsa gives immediate dependent origination.
Anālayo gives satipaṭṭhāna as direct observational method.

Nibbāna: The Mind Stilled is the capstone: the direct interpretation of cessation as the cooling, quenching, and non-establishment of the fabricated world.

3. Structure Map

Macro-structure: 33 sermons.

Functional movement:

Clarification before purification
Reframes Nibbāna against wrong views, metaphysical confusions, and inherited doctrinal fog.
Fire, cooling, and quenching
Explores the imagery of Nibbāna as extinguishing, not as nihilism but as release from fuel.
Consciousness and non-manifestation
Tracks the difficult early Buddhist language around consciousness, cessation, and non-establishment.
Name-and-form / consciousness loop
Shows how experience stabilizes as a mutually conditioning system.
Signs, concepts, and world-building
Links perception, nimitta, designation, and papañca to the fabrication of “world.”
Voidness and cessation
Moves toward emptiness as experiential deconstruction rather than philosophical slogan.
Nibbāna as the end of re-rendering
The world is not destroyed; the delusive mode of worlding is stilled.
