8. Editorial Review

This source should be treated as a master interpretive spine, not merely one Buddhist book among others. It is perfect for Imaginarium because it translates Nibbāna into a precise deconstruction of how experience becomes world, how world becomes self, and how self-world loses its fuel.

Avoid making it sound mystical in a vague way. Ñāṇananda is not saying “reality is imagination” in a loose esoteric sense. He is showing how experience, under ignorance, is dependently rendered through contact, perception, sign, craving, designation, and consciousness.

9. Variety Review

