8. Editorial Review

This source should function as the embodied training manual of the Buddhist companion volume.

It prevents the project from becoming merely intellectual. Ñāṇananda and Ñāṇavīra can show the structure of delusion, but Ṭhānissaro shows where the structure can be trained: in breath, attention, perception, effort, evaluation, and bodily feeling.

For the Imaginarium frame, the key insight is:

The rendered self-world is not only analyzed; it is re-trained through skillful fabrication.

Do not present this as dreamy breath mysticism. The strength of the text is its pragmatic intelligence: adjust, observe, evaluate, settle, refine, release.

