Core function: the key early Buddhist study of papañca: conceptual proliferation, distortion, designation, perceptual construction, and the self-world spun out through language and craving.

2. Buddhist Lineage Placement

This is Ñāṇananda’s conceptual-proliferation engine.

Where Nibbāna: The Mind Stilled gives the grand de-rendering of Nibbāna, Concept and Reality isolates one of the main mechanisms by which the rendering becomes binding: papañca.

Compared with the other sources:

Ñāṇavīra gives the existential structure of self-view.
Ṭhānissaro gives trainable fabrication through breath.
Concept and Reality shows how concept, perception, sign, and language generate the self-world.
Magic of the Mind dramatizes the same process as perceptual enchantment.
Law of Dependent Arising supplies the causal architecture.
Nāgārjuna expands the anti-reification into Madhyamaka emptiness.
Visuddhimagga systematizes path, jhāna, and insight.
Buddhadāsa makes dependent arising immediate.
Anālayo supplies satipaṭṭhāna as direct observation.
3. Structure Map

Macro-structure: a compact scholarly-commentarial essay.

Functional movement:

Problem setup
“Concept” and “reality” are not neutral categories. Ordinary experience is already conceptually mediated.
Papañca and papañca-saññā-saṅkhā
Defines the key doctrinal terms: proliferation and the perceptions/notions born from proliferation.
Sutta basis
Uses early Buddhist discourses to show how perception, contact, feeling, craving, and self-reference generate proliferated thought.
Conceptual distortion
Shows how language and designation harden fluid experience into “things,” “selves,” and “world.”
Not-self deepened
Not-self is not just “there is no soul”; it is a critique of the conceptual machinery that keeps producing self-world.
Commentarial and scholarly review
Later interpretations are examined and corrected where they obscure the experiential force of papañca.
Mahāyāna bridge
The text includes discussion of prapañca in Mahāyāna Buddhism, making it useful as a bridge toward Nāgārjuna.
