Access status: official free-distribution PDF via Seeing Through the Net; also available through BPS PDF hosting. The PDF states it is “published strictly for free distribution,” so use summary-heavy treatment and only short quotes.

1. Source Identity

Full title: The Magic of the Mind: An Exposition of the Kālakārāma Sutta
Author: Bhikkhu Kaṭukurunde Ñāṇananda
Original BPS edition: 1972; later revised free-distribution editions.
Core function: a compact study of perception, consciousness, illusion, and release through the Kālakārāma Sutta.

This is the perceptual-enchantment source: how consciousness, name-and-form, signs, and viewpoints generate a convincing “magic show” of world-experience.

2. Buddhist Lineage Placement

This source sits between Concept and Reality and Nibbāna: The Mind Stilled.

Concept and Reality explains conceptual proliferation.
The Magic of the Mind shows the lived perceptual illusion: consciousness as magician, the world as conjuring.
Nibbāna: The Mind Stilled expands this into the full de-rendering of Nibbāna.

Compared with the rest:

Ñāṇavīra gives the existential skeleton.
Ṭhānissaro gives trainable fabrication.
Law of Dependent Arising gives causal mechanics.
Nāgārjuna gives emptiness dialectic.
Visuddhimagga gives path-system architecture.
Buddhadāsa gives immediate dependent origination.
Anālayo gives satipaṭṭhāna observation.
3. Structure Map

Macro-structure: a short exposition around the Kālakārāma Sutta.

Functional movement:

The Buddha’s strange mode of knowing
The Kālakārāma Sutta presents a radically non-grasping relation to seen, heard, sensed, and cognized.
Consciousness as magician
Experience appears as if stable, external, and self-evident, but this apparent solidity is constructed.
Name-and-form as the net
Consciousness is caught in the net of name-and-form when it takes objects as arresting points of fixation.
The collapse of viewpoint
Liberation is not a superior viewpoint; it is release from viewpoint-making.
Seeing without conceit
The arahant sees without constructing a seer, a seen thing, or a “thing worth seeing.”
Release from enchantment
The magic show is not destroyed as an object; its spell is understood.
