8. Editorial Review

This source is one of the best Imaginarium bridges because it speaks the language of appearance, illusion, enchantment, and release without becoming loose mysticism.

The core editorial framing:

Ordinary experience is not false in the crude sense; it is enchanted. The error is not that nothing appears, but that appearances are taken as self-evident, owned, and worth clinging to.

For Path of Re-Rendering, this gives the Buddhist equivalent of “the rendered theatre”: the mind stages a world, inhabits it, and then suffers inside its own show.

9. Variety Review

To avoid repetition:

Do not reduce the whole source to “life is illusion.”
Keep the precision: illusion means misapprehension, fixation, conceit, and viewpoint-making.
Rotate essays between consciousness, name-and-form, viewpoint, object-fixation, non-seer perception, and de-enchantment.
Pair with:
Concept and Reality for papañca.
Nibbāna: The Mind Stilled for cessation.
Ñāṇavīra for self-view.
Nāgārjuna for emptiness.
Anālayo for direct observation of perception.
