Ñāṇananda — The Law of Dependent Arising

Access status: official free-distribution PDF via Seeing Through the Net. The PDF states it is “published strictly for free distribution” and that profit/material gain is prohibited, so use summary-heavy treatment and only short quotations.

1. Source Identity

Full title: The Law of Dependent Arising: The Secret of Bondage and Release
Author: Bhikkhu Kaṭukurunde Ñāṇananda
Form: systematic Dhamma exposition on paṭicca-samuppāda.
Core function: the causal architecture source: how ignorance, formations, consciousness, name-and-form, contact, feeling, craving, clinging, becoming, birth, ageing-and-death form the machinery of bondage — and how their cessation opens release.

2. Buddhist Lineage Placement

This is Ñāṇananda’s dependent-arising engine.

Concept and Reality explains conceptual proliferation.
The Magic of the Mind shows perceptual enchantment.
Nibbāna: The Mind Stilled shows cessation as de-rendering.
The Law of Dependent Arising shows the actual mechanism: how the rendered world is generated, maintained, and released.

Compared with the others:

Ñāṇavīra = existential structure.
Ṭhānissaro = trainable fabrication.
Nāgārjuna = emptiness dialectic.
Visuddhimagga = encyclopaedic path map.
Buddhadāsa = radical immediacy of dependent origination.
Anālayo = mindfulness observation of the arising process.
3. Structure Map

Functional movement:

Dependent arising as noble norm
Not a theory of the universe first, but a penetrative law of bondage and release.
Ignorance and formations
Ignorance does not simply lack data; it mis-structures experience. Formations carry that mis-structuring forward.
Consciousness and name-and-form
The central feedback loop: consciousness depends on name-and-form, and name-and-form depends on consciousness.
Six sense bases, contact, feeling
The world becomes experiential through contact; feeling gives affective charge.
Craving and clinging
Feeling becomes thirst; thirst becomes appropriation.
Becoming and birth
Identity-worlds are enacted, inhabited, and renewed.
Ageing-and-death / sorrow / despair
The cost of taking the constructed process personally.
Cessation sequence
Liberation is the fading of fuel, not the destruction of a metaphysical self.
