Nāgārjuna — Mūlamadhyamakakārikā

Access status: root Sanskrit text is freely accessible through Digital Sanskrit Buddhist Canon and GRETIL-style reference texts; scanned editions also exist on Internet Archive. English translations by Garfield, Kalupahana, Siderits/Katsura, and others are generally copyrighted or ambiguously hosted, so this blueprint should be summary-heavy, using chapter structure and short verse references rather than importing long translation passages.

1. Source Identity

Source: Mūlamadhyamakakārikā, “Root Verses on the Middle Way”
Author: Nāgārjuna
Form: 27-chapter verse treatise.
Lineage: foundational Madhyamaka text of Mahāyāna Buddhist philosophy. Google Books describes it as the foundational text of the Madhyamaka school and a touchstone presentation of emptiness.


Core function: the anti-reification blade: if all things arise dependently, nothing stands by its own intrinsic essence.

For Imaginarium, this is the source that prevents “rendering” from becoming a subtle metaphysical substance. The rendered world is empty; the rendering process is empty; emptiness itself is empty.

2. Buddhist Lineage Placement

Nāgārjuna is the radical emptiness expansion of dependent arising.

Where Ñāṇananda shows the world as dependently rendered through contact, name-and-form, consciousness, signs, and cessation, Nāgārjuna dismantles the philosophical assumption that anything in that rendered field possesses self-existence.

Where Ñāṇavīra refuses consoling metaphysics, Nāgārjuna performs the same refusal through dialectic: cause, motion, self, time, aggregates, bondage, release, saṃsāra, and nirvāṇa are all unfindable as intrinsically existing entities.

Compared with the other sources:

Ñāṇananda’s Nibbāna sermons = phenomenology of cessation.
Ñāṇavīra = existential structure and self-view.
Ṭhānissaro = skillful fabrication in practice.
Concept and Reality = papañca and conceptual proliferation.
Magic of the Mind = perceptual enchantment.
Law of Dependent Arising = causal mechanics.
MMK = emptiness of all reified structures.
Visuddhimagga = systematic Theravāda path architecture.
Buddhadāsa = immediate dependent origination.
Anālayo = observational mindfulness.
3. Structure Map

Macro-structure: 27 chapters, each dismantling one candidate for intrinsic existence.

Chapter functions:

Conditions — causality cannot be grounded in self-existence.
Motion — mover, movement, and path cannot be isolated.
Sense faculties — perception has no independent perceiver/faculty/object foundation.
Aggregates — personhood cannot be reduced to or separated from aggregates.
Elements — basic constituents lack own-being.
Desire and the desirous one — craving and subject cannot be made self-standing.
Arising, enduring, ceasing — temporal production cannot be found intrinsically.
Agent and action — doer and deed arise dependently.
Prior entity — no self can be established before experience.
Fire and fuel — identity/difference logic collapses around support and supported.
Beginning and end — saṃsāric sequence has no graspable first point.
Suffering — suffering is not self-produced, other-produced, both, or causeless.
Formations — conditioned constructions are empty.
Contact — contact cannot be isolated as a self-existing event.
Essence — direct critique of svabhāva, intrinsic nature.
Bondage and liberation — no inherently bound being is later inherently released.
Action and result — karma works dependently, not through eternal substance.
Self — self cannot be found as identical with or different from aggregates.
Time — past, present, future are mutually dependent designations.
Combination — cause/effect relation cannot be reified.
Becoming and destruction — arising/perishing cannot stand independently.
Tathāgata — even Buddha-language cannot be grasped metaphysically.
Error — ignorance and distortion are empty, yet function.
Four Noble Truths — emptiness safeguards, rather than destroys, dependent arising and path.
Nirvāṇa — nirvāṇa is not an intrinsically existing opposite of saṃsāra.
Twelve links — dependent arising summarized as bondage and cessation.
Views — liberation requires release from metaphysical views.
