1. Source Identity

Source: Visuddhimagga, “The Path of Purification”
Author: Buddhaghosa
Translator: Bhikkhu Ñāṇamoli
Date: 5th-century Theravāda commentary, composed in Sri Lanka.
Form: massive classical manual of Theravāda doctrine, meditation, and purification.

Core function: the encyclopaedic path-map: virtue, concentration, meditation objects, jhāna, insight, aggregates, dependent arising, knowledge, purification, and liberation.

2. Buddhist Lineage Placement

The Visuddhimagga is the system architecture source.

Where Ñāṇananda deconstructs the rendered world, Ñāṇavīra cuts self-view, Ṭhānissaro trains fabrication, and Nāgārjuna empties all reifications, Buddhaghosa organizes the whole classical Theravāda path into a technical curriculum.

Its role is not subtle imaginal prose but map, taxonomy, discipline, and sequence.

3. Structure Map

Macro-structure: three great divisions:

Sīla / Virtue
Ethical purification, restraint, livelihood, conduct, and the stabilizing of the practitioner.
Samādhi / Concentration
Meditation objects, kasina practice, breath, divine abidings, immaterial attainments, and jhāna.
Paññā / Wisdom
Aggregates, sense bases, elements, faculties, truths, dependent arising, insight knowledges, path, fruition, and purification.

Functional arc: purify conduct → stabilize attention → analyze experience → see impermanence, suffering, not-self → realize path and release.

