1. Source Identity

Source: Paticcasamuppada: Practical Dependent Origination
Author: Buddhadāsa Bhikkhu
Lineage: Thai reformist Theravāda, Suan Mokkh, practical early-Buddhist reinterpretation.
Core function: dependent origination as an immediate, experiential process of suffering and cessation — not merely a three-lifetime cosmological chart.

Buddhadāsa frames paṭiccasamuppāda as “the heart of Buddhism” and the “fullness of the Noble Truths.”

2. Buddhist Lineage Placement

Buddhadāsa is the immediacy corrective.

Where Buddhaghosa’s Visuddhimagga gives a vast classical system, Buddhadāsa strips dependent origination back to practical urgency: this is happening now, in contact, feeling, craving, clinging, becoming, and suffering.

Compared with the others:

Ñāṇananda gives phenomenological depth and sign/world deconstruction.
Ñāṇavīra gives existential severity.
Ṭhānissaro gives breath-fabrication training.
Concept and Reality gives papañca.
Magic of the Mind gives perceptual illusion.
Law of Dependent Arising gives Ñāṇananda’s causal architecture.
Nāgārjuna gives emptiness of intrinsic existence.
Visuddhimagga gives classical taxonomy.
Anālayo gives satipaṭṭhāna observation.
3. Structure Map

Functional movement:

Why dependent origination matters
It is presented as the central practical law of Buddhism: the beginning and ending of suffering.
Critique of misunderstanding
Buddhadāsa challenges readings that move the decisive causes of suffering into inaccessible past-life explanations.
Immediate-cycle interpretation
The twelve links are read as operating in lived experience, sometimes with great speed.
Contact as the battlefield
Sense contact becomes the decisive point where ignorance or wisdom determines the chain.
Feeling to craving
Vedanā becomes the hinge: feeling either conditions craving or is known with mindfulness.
Clinging, becoming, birth
Identity is repeatedly born through appropriation: “I,” “me,” “mine,” role, mood, story.
Cessation in this life
If the chain is seen at contact/feeling, suffering can cease here and now.
