8. Editorial Review

The Sutta Nipāta should function as the austere poetic root of the Buddhist companion volume.

Its genius is not system. Its genius is cutting away the need for system-as-identity. It repeatedly asks: what remains when one no longer builds a self out of desire, doctrine, purity, speech, social standing, or metaphysical position?

For Path of Re-Rendering, the clean formulation is:

The world is not only rendered by perception; it is defended by views. Release requires the collapse of the position from which “my world” is argued, purified, and protected.

